The article entitled "Picoeukaryotic diversity in the Gulf of Gab{\`{e}}s: variability patterns and relationships to nutrients and water masses", intend to explore the variation of picoeukaryotes communities due to physicochemical factors, in a particular environment with contrasting characteristics, where information about this group is lacking. In the environment analyzed (the gulf of Gab{\`{e}}s), previous data indicate the picoplankton is a huge contributor to the overall chlorophyll biomass. Besides, previous data based on pigments analysis indicates a particular pattern in terms of diversity of picoplanktonic communities, different from other Mediterranean regions dominated by prymnesiophytes. To assess their research goals, the authors used a mixed culture-independent methodology based on fingerprinting techniques and high throughput sequencing of ribosomal genes, using samples obtained during tree courses in the specified region. The authors intend to relate the community composition observed, with environmental parameters like nutrients and temperature, but also with the different water masses present in the region.  The article is well written, with a clear statement of the work objectives. The experimental design and the methods are clearly explained and detailed. Their results showed clearly observed patterns in picoeukaryotes assemblages, driven by the coast offshore gradient, the vertical variations in the offshore stations, the sampling period, and the co-occurrence of different water masses  I find the article very consistent and rigorous. However, I do believe the figures can be much improved, with no a huge load of work for the authors.  1. Figure 2 has the heading a bit blurry, maybe because the authors try to decrease the size to fit it in a composite figure. Please, modify the axis labels. Authors can also include a label (a dot, for example) indicating the depth where they collect the sample, so for the reader will be more easily have a broad picture of the physicochemical parameters in relation to the samples.  2. Figure 3: the authors can flip the DGGE and try to arrange the different lanes in front of the respective branch in the cluster. This will allow the reader to follow more easily the observed patterns. In the same figure, NMDS symbols can be added to the plot, instead of the names of the samples. Default colors used by Primer software are not always the better. Also, please include the label of the X axis on the cluster. Is that similarity? Dissimilarity? Coefficient?  3. Figure 4 and 6 can be fused in one single figure, and they can follow the same scheme than in figure 3. Instead the DGGE, use the heatmap at the side of the cluster. No need of the piecharts if the authors add that info as a hestmap.  4. Figure 7 is critical since is the figure that represents the hypothesis test about the influence of environmental parameters over picoeukaryotes composition. However, in my opinion, the figure is really difficult to follow. I do not believe the circular plots (that shown axis deviations) and the eigenvalues histogram are really needed to give the message. The main graphs (the ordination ones) could also be fused in a single plot, were the X canonical axis (the taxonomy) and the Y canonical axis (the environment) can be easily interpreted in function of total samples distribution.  Other comments to the authors.  5. The authors mention in the methods section that they use PR2 database for taxonomic assignation, but also two in-house databases. Nothing is detailed about the similarities or differences observed between databases. There were consistent? Or they used an integrated database? Please clarify.  6. Since they observe clear clusters, why don't try to add a SIMPROF test to the clusters? In this way, the authors can test if the aggrupation of the different samples is significant (i.e. not due to random processes). This test can be easily run using the same software the authors are using for the clusters (PRIMER). 
